  // -- FAQ --
  faq: [
    { question: 'What types of household worksheets can I create?', answer: 'You can generate a wide variety of household-themed worksheets including room-based object sorting activities, preposition practice with room scenes, daily routine sequencing exercises, counting objects in household illustrations, matching household items that go together, shadow matching with common home objects, coloring pages of room interiors, word searches with household vocabulary, and odd-one-out puzzles identifying items that do not belong in a room.' },
    { question: 'Are the household worksheets free to use?', answer: 'Yes, LessonCraftStudio lets you create and download household-themed worksheets at no cost. Choose your preferred worksheet type, select the household theme, customize settings like difficulty and number of items, and generate a printable PDF ready for your classroom or home learning session.' },
    { question: 'What age groups are household worksheets suitable for?', answer: 'Household worksheets are designed for children ages 3 through 9, covering preschool through third grade. Younger children work with simple room sorting, basic prepositions, and coloring, while older students tackle multi-step word problems, complex spatial descriptions, extended routine sequences, and informational reading about homes and daily life.' },
    { question: 'How do household worksheets teach spatial reasoning?', answer: 'Household scenes are naturally rich in spatial relationships because rooms contain objects in many positions relative to each other. Preposition worksheets ask children to identify, describe, and create spatial arrangements using words like on, under, between, behind, and above. This repeated practice with meaningful spatial language builds the mental model of space that supports geometry and measurement skills.' },
    { question: 'Can household worksheets help children learn about daily routines?', answer: 'Yes, daily routine sequencing is one of the strongest applications of the household theme. Worksheets present morning routines, bedtime routines, or household chore sequences in scrambled order and ask children to arrange steps correctly. This develops temporal reasoning, procedural literacy, and the understanding that some steps depend on others, a cognitive skill that transfers to every academic discipline.' },
    { question: 'How do household worksheets develop vocabulary?', answer: 'Children learn room names like kitchen, bathroom, and bedroom, object names like cabinet, curtain, and appliance, spatial terms like above, beside, and beneath, and routine vocabulary like schedule, organize, and prepare. These words are immediately reinforced through daily life as children encounter the real objects and spaces in their own homes.' },
    { question: 'What safety concepts do household worksheets teach?', answer: 'Household worksheets introduce home safety through engaging activities rather than lectures. Children sort items as safe versus requires adult supervision, identify potential hazards in room illustrations, and reason about why safety rules like not running on stairs or keeping cleaning supplies locked exist. This builds both safety awareness and cause-and-effect reasoning.' },
    { question: 'How do household worksheets support preposition learning?', answer: 'The household context is ideal for prepositions because homes are full of objects in varied spatial relationships. Worksheets show a teddy bear on, under, in, beside, between, and behind furniture, asking children to match descriptions to positions. Because children experience these same arrangements at home daily, the vocabulary gains are continuously reinforced through natural daily living.' },
    { question: 'Are household worksheets good for homeschooling?', answer: 'Household worksheets are arguably the most practical theme for homeschooling because the learning environment is the subject matter. Every room becomes a lesson extension, every routine reinforces sequencing, and every object is a potential math counter or vocabulary word. Parents can teach directly from the worksheets and immediately apply concepts to the home around them without any additional materials.' },
    { question: 'How often should children complete household worksheets?', answer: 'Two to four sessions per week works well for building spatial vocabulary, classification skills, and routine awareness. Each session should last ten to twenty minutes depending on age. Because household concepts are continuously reinforced through daily life, even brief worksheet sessions can produce lasting learning gains when combined with everyday conversations about rooms, objects, and routines.' },
  ],

